2. A short description of Titanic data that I will be using in my project, and objective of the data analysis.

We are all familiar with Titanic tragedy. There were approximately 2224 passengers and crew aboard the ship, more than 1500 of died. The data includes 1309 observations, and 14 variables.

I would like to apply Machine learning tools to conduct some analysis on Titanic data to predict what type of people were likely to survive. My label variable (Y) is survifor or died, y is equal 1 if the person survived and equal 0, if the person died. Bascially, I am going to use the data and apply machine learning algrithms which will learn from the data the pattern between who survived and who did not.

3. Feature engineering

Droping the variable with missing values may not be a good approach for this data because if I do that, I will end up with only 119 observations. Therefore, I am going to do feature engineering which is one of the method that helps to imporve model performance prediction. I am going to look at every feature and try to understand it and decide whether I should use it for the model/prediction.

3.1. pclass

The first feature in str(titanic3) is pclass.

Looking at the descriptive of the data, pclass is actually a proxy for socioeconomic status. Basically, class 1, for those who are richer and class 3 for those who are poor. Now, I wanted to see if there are missing values in pclass

table(is.na(titanic3$pclass)|titanic3$pclass == 'na') #there are no missing values!

##  1309

## 
## 1st 2nd 3rd

The distribution across the classes shows that there are a lot more people in third class than class 1 and 2 which makes sense. Interestingly, when I look at the second class, I expect to see more people in the second class than first class. But this is not the case. This patterns can be interesting when we run the models. It is goog to keep that in mind.

Visuallizing pclass and survivied

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(titanic3, aes(x = pclass, fill = factor(survived))) + geom_bar(width = 0.1) + xlab("Pclass") + ylab("Total count") + labs(fill = "Survived")

From the plot: generally speaking, if you are in the 3th class, you (unfortunately) are more likely to die under the condition all things are equal. However, if you are in the first class, it seems you would have a better chance to survive.

Therefore, I will create a new variable/feature I call “title”

extracttitle <- function(name){
  name <- as.character(name)
  
  if(length(grep("Miss.", name)) > 0){
    return("Miss.")
  } else if (length(grep("Master.", name)) > 0){
    return("Master.")
  } else if (length(grep("Mrs.", name)) > 0){
    return("Mrs.")
  } else {
    return("Other")
  }
}

titles <- c()

for(i in 1:nrow(titanic3)){
  titles <- c(titles, extracttitle(titanic3[i, "name"]))
}

titanic3$title <- as.factor(titles)

Here I will use LPM, logistic, KNN, and CART models and then I will select the model that give me higher means AUC and less variation.

LPM and Logistic

library(caret)
library(MASS)
library(ROCR)

df <- titanic3
df$y <- titanic3$survived
df <- df[, -2] #dropped survived
df <- df[, -7] #dropped embarked because it creates an error when I run Glm, it says factor has new levels. 
df$y <- as.factor(df$y)

set.seed(1)

df$y_lm <- as.numeric(df$y)
df$y_lg <- as.factor(df$y)


# Containers
AUC_lm <- c()
AUC_log <- c()


# Loop

for (i in 1:1300) {
ind <- sample(nrow(df), nrow(df)*0.70, replace = FALSE)
tr <- df[ind, ]
tt <- df[-ind,]
# LPM
model <- lm(y_lm ~ ., data = tr[, -c(8,10)])
phat <- predict(model, tt[, -c(8,10)])

# AUC-LM
pred_rocr <- prediction(phat, tt$y_lm)
auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocr, measure = "auc")
AUC_lm[i] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]

# Logistic
model <- glm(y_lg ~ ., data = tr[, -c(8,9)], family = "binomial")
phat <- predict(model, tt[, -c(8,9)], "response")

#AUC
pred_rocr <- prediction(phat, tt$y)
auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocr, measure = "auc")
AUC_log[i] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
}

mean(AUC_lm)
## [1] 0.8514344
mean(AUC_log)
## [1] 0.8522095
sqrt(var(AUC_lm))
## [1] 0.01803657
sqrt(var(AUC_log))

# KNN

library(caret)
library(MASS)
library(ROCR)

df <- titanic3
df$y <- titanic3$survived
df <- df[, -2] #dropped survived
df <- df[, -7] #dropped embarked because it creates an error when I run Glm, it says factor has new levels. 
#df$embarked <- as.integer(df$embarked)

set.seed(1)

df$y_lm <- as.numeric(df$y)
df$y_lm[df$y_lm==1] <- 0
df$y_lm[df$y_lm==2] <- 1

df$y_lg <- as.factor(df$y)
df$y_knn <- as.factor(df$y)
# Containers

kopt <- c()
MAUC <- c()
AUCk <- c()
# Loop

k <- seq(from = 3, to = 40, by = 1)

for(i in 1:1300){
ind <- sample(nrow(df), nrow(df)*0.70, replace = FALSE)
tr <- df[ind, ]
tt <- df[-ind, ]

for(s in 1:length(k)){
model <- knn3(y_knn ~., data = tr[, -c(8, 9, 10)], k = k[s])
phat <- predict(model, tt[, -c(8,9,10)], type = "prob")
#AUC
pred_rocr <- prediction(phat[,2], tt$y)
auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocr, measure = "auc")
AUCk[s] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
}
kopt[i] <- k[which.max(AUCk)]
MAUC[i] <- AUCk[which.max(AUCk)]
}

CART: decision tree

remove(list = ls())

extracttitle <- function(name){
  name <- as.character(name)
  
  if(length(grep("Miss.", name)) > 0){
    return("Miss.")
  } else if (length(grep("Master.", name)) > 0){
    return("Master.")
  } else if (length(grep("Mrs.", name)) > 0){
    return("Mrs.")
  } else {
    return("Other")
  }
}

titles <- c()

for(i in 1:nrow(titanic3)){
  titles <- c(titles, extracttitle(titanic3[i, "name"]))
}

titanic3$title <- as.factor(titles)
library(PASWR)
library(ROCR)
library(rpart)

# Data
#remove(list = ls())
#data(titanic3)
df <- titanic3

# Containers
MAUC <- c()
AUC <- c()

# Complexity Parameter (cp)
cpgrid <- seq(from = 0.01, to = 0.05, by = 0.001)

# Loop
set.seed(1)
for(i in 1:100){
  ind <- sample(nrow(df), nrow(df), replace = TRUE)
  ind <- unique(ind)
  tr <- df[ind, ]
  tt <- df[-ind, ]

  for(s in 1:length(cpgrid)){
    model <- rpart(survived ~ pclass + sex + age + sibsp + parch + fare + title,
                  data=tr, method="class",
                  control = rpart.control(minsplit = 2, minbucket = 1,
                  cp = 0))
    pmodel <- prune(model, cp = cpgrid[s])
    phat <- predict(pmodel, tt, type = "prob")
      
    #AUC
    pred_rocr <- prediction(phat[,2], tt$survived)
    auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocr, measure = "auc")
    AUC[s] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
  }
MAUC[i] <- max(AUC)
}
mean(MAUC)
## [1] 0.8175358
sqrt(var(MAUC))
## [1] 0.01971923

Which model should I choose?

I have selected LPM because it has higher means and lower variance. There is a slightly difference between LPM performance and logistic performance, logistic is a little better than LPM. However, I decided to select LPM because it has higher level of interpretation.
